summary: A makeup artist is shown applying makeup to a model. The video begins with the artist applying product to the model's neck with a brush. Then, the artist applies concealer to the model's eyelids and then powder. The artist continues to apply eyeshadow, blending different shades on the eyelids and outer corners. The artist then applies darker shadow and liner, blending it out. Individual lashes are applied, followed by foundation. The artist applies contour and blush to the model's face. The video shows the artist blending the contour and blush, and then setting the under-eye area with powder. The artist then applies bronzer and blush again. Finally, the artist lines the model's lips and applies lip gloss.

summary: The video shows a person spearfishing in the ocean. The creator explains the importance of hiding behind rocks or coral to not be seen by fish. They briefly mention not being able to spear parrotfish in Florida due to protection laws. The creator then encounters a school of fish and later spots and attempts to spear a hogfish, but it escapes.

on_screen_text: Catching My Food, Location: South Florida
key_video_elements: Creator, Food, Technology, Nature, Vehicles, Props
transcript: Catching my food. Whenever you're hunting, you want to make sure that you're hiding behind any rock or coral so that the fish that you want to eat doesn't see you. I locked onto a large parrotfish, and while these guys do look big and tasty, you're not allowed to spear them because they're protected here in Florida. As I was following it, I ran out of air, so I decided to swim to the top and from the top of the water, I saw a massive school of fish. Sometimes there's something tasty hiding in the school, so I went down to take a closer look, but when I didn't find anything, I waved them off and continued my search for what could be my breakfast. I stumbled across the most delicious fish in the sea, which is a hogfish, and when I took aim, I needed to make sure that I hit it good because these guys are destroying South Florida. That one fish wasn't going to be enough to feed me though, so I had to be extra stealthy. As I went across the bottom of the sea floor, looking for what else I can eat, I swam up to this hogfish that thought it was completely camouflage. And when it realized that I saw it, it turned its camouflage off and slowly started swimming away from me. Well, this fish is delicious. It has to be a minimum of 16 inches, and this guy was just...

summary: The video demonstrates how to create a first beat using a digital audio workstation. It outlines three simple steps: starting with drums, laying down a kick and snare pattern, adding extra kicks for bounce and hi-hats, and then adding a melody using a piano or synth. The creator encourages viewers to make their first beat, post it, and tag them.
on_screen_text: POV, making your first beat, can be intimidating, but it's easier than, today, I'm breaking it down into, three simple steps, anyone can follow, start from the drums, pick a basic drum kit, go for a kick, and a hi-hat, lay down a basic, kick and snare pattern, start with the kick, on beat 1, and the snare on beat 3, if you want to add a bounce, add some extra kicks, and add the hi-hats, on every beat, nothing fancy, but it does have a groove, the bassline is what, makes your beat feel powerful, start with a synth bass, I like the wonk bass, preset on Ableton, keep your bassline, simple, it's your first beat, I'll use the notes A, C and G, now add a melody, pick an instrument, like piano or a synth, I'll just pick piano, and here's a trick, try to stick to only, 3 or 4 notes, go make your first beat, post it and tag me, I want to hear, what you create
